'''ARM ''Oaxaca'' (PO-161)''' is the lead ship of the {{sclass-|Oaxaca|patrol vessel|4}} of patrol vessels, constructed by and for the [[Mexican Navy]].

It has a length of {{convert|282.2|ft|1}}, a draft of {{convert|11.8|ft|1}}, a beam of {{convert|34.4|ft|1}}, and displaces {{convert|1850|ST|MT|1}}.<ref>
{{cite web
|url= http://www.semar.gob.mx/boletin/2003/bol_036_03.htm
|accessdate= 2007-11-17
|title= Botadura de un nuevo buque para la armada de M<U+00E9>xico
|work= Boletines
|date= April 11, 2003
|publisher= Secretaria de Marina, Armada de M<U+00E9>xico
|language= Spanish
|archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20071008051940/http://www.semar.gob.mx/boletin/2003/bol_036_03.htm |archivedate = 2007-10-08}}
</ref>

Primary armament is a single [[Otobreda 76 mm|OTO Melara 76 mm naval gun]], with a pair of [[OTO Melara]] 12.7&nbsp;mm remote controlled naval turret Mod. 517 with [[M2 Browning machine gun|M2 12.7mm]] [[machine guns]] on each side, and an [[Oto Melara]] single 30/SAFS 30&nbsp;mm cannon aft.

A helipad on the afterdeck has handling capabilities for a variety of helicopters, such as the [[Eurocopter AS565|Panther]], [[Eurocopter Fennec|Fennec]], or the [[MBB Bo 105|Bolkow Bo 105 Super-5]].

The ship has a cruising speed of {{convert|20|kn|km/h}}, carries a complement of 77, and has provisions to carry a group of 39 special forces and/or marines for a variety of missions.

==UNITAS Gold==
ARM Oaxaca participated in UNITAS Gold from 25 April 2009 to 5 May 2009.<ref>http://www.navy.mil/search/display.asp?story_id=44924&page=2</ref> The ships main guns were tested as well as a BO-105 helicopter from the ship during the sinking of the ex-USS Connelly (DD 975) 29 April. This was the first time Mexico participated in UNITAS Gold, sending ARM ''Oaxaca'' and ARM ''Mina''. The ships also practiced fire drills and other exercises.

